John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it continues in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding exam results, which are further enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other endeavors in the local environment.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can put together and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we find that modern language remains a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it strikes the heart.”
It’s an important reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can look at the latest exam results this year that language ranks highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS’ 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French, and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important competences that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as subject choice at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools pensa and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17% of employers were unable to fill vacancies due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in terms of preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career they choose, if they have learned a different language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a head start to competitors.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language education for those who are children today.
Speaking multiple languages, especially languages from developing countries, gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, schools differ in what languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important for the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills required to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that language continues to be really important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to Scotland’s youth.
You have to do it right.
