Students at Harvard take a course on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture, where one studies all night held up by large amounts of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world’s best university often don’t know the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has made the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation on the effects of lack of sleep on learning.
“When the presentation was finished, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why do I first get to know this now that I’m on the candidate?’
“She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits can improve one’s academic and sporting performance as well as one’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health field, says the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists, among other things, of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a college room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to gain knowledge about the effects of caffeine and light, and how one’s athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and how important good sleep habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression, and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of the campus.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride in taking an allnighter still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
The “secret weapon” against stress, fatigue and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain because lack of sleep makes the brain think that one is starving, why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler organize the course last year when he took one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and made him work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next thing will be that all graduates are offered a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to get up. This can raise awareness of the harmful effects of light from electronic displays, which can move at the circadian rhythm and make it harder to fall asleep.
