Algae bloom update: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general declining algae concentration in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, there are reports of widespread flowering in the area around Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting that the concentration is declining.
The bloom of algae spreads over a 210 km coastline from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
There are less blooms about 16 km from the coast in Hillsborough County, but there are fewer than last week.
Flowering has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported in or at sea in Pinellas County during the last week, low to high concentrations in the sea off in Hillsborough County, background concentration to high concentrations in Manatee County, background concentration to high concentrations in or in the sea off the coast of Sarasota County, background concentration to medium concentrations in the county of Charlotte County.
Respiratory problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of breathing problems in northwest Florida in the past week.
